                    Custom Vue Directives
                    Course Notes


1 - Understanding Vue.js Directives
Directives are special element attributes
  - They begin with the "v-" prefix
  - Some of the more common examples are v-for, v-if, v-model
  - The directive attribute values are expected to be a single JS expression
  - The job of a directive is to apply side-effects to the DOM based on that expression

Example Syntax
  // Some example directives
  <div id="app">
    <p v-if="age<10">
      You are too young !!!
    </p>
  </div>
  
  // The v-bind directive
  <div id="app">
    // This binds the href link to the data property
    // v-bind can be used to bind any source of attributes
    // The value of the directive is inside the quotes
    <p v-bind:href"homepageurl" v-bind:title="linkTitle">
      You are too young !!!
    </p>
  </div>
  
  // The v-on directive
  <div id="app">
    // v-on accepts an argument for the event to listen to
    // The expression is to be ran when the event takes place
    // How v-on behaves can be controlled using modifiers
    // the are defined using a dot and the modifier name and there can be more than one
    <p v-bind:href"homepageurl" v-on:click.prevent.once="Home">
      You are too young !!!
    </p>
  </div>

